instead of using username and password every time for using command ssh, generate a key pair in this way:
step 1:
$ ssh-keygen -t rsa      
//in the output it requires to enter passphrase, which is optional; if set, you need to enter it every time 
//in the output it also shows the file paths where public and private keys are stored
step 2:
copy the public key to remote server, to do this, you'll have to input your password at least once
$ ssh-copy-id bob@remoteserver
//input password at some point
//by now public key is stored in a hidden file on remote server /home/bob/.ssh/authorized_keys

scp command: allows you to copy files to the remote server
$ scp /home/bob/file.tar.gz remoteservername:/home/bob
$ scp -pr /home/bob/blabla/ remoteservername:/home/bob      //copy a folder to the remote server and preserve the ownership and permission of the source file by -p, -r recursively


ip tables: to restrict network access among different hosts
$ sudo apt install iptables
$ sudo iptables -L                //list default rules which allow all the input, output and forward connections
set a rule for the remote server:
$ iptables -A INPUT -p tcp -s 172.16.238.187 --dport 22 -j ACCEPT
//-A add rules, -p protocol, -s source followed by the client server, -d destination, -j action to take
$ iptables -L                     //verify
$ iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j DROP        //drop the input connection from all servers, and since it reads rules sequentially in the ip table, it would only allows input connection from 172.16.238.187
$ iptables -I OUTPUT -p tcp -d 172.16.238.100 --dport 443 -j ACCEPT        //-I insert the rule to the top of the table instead of to the bottom
$ iptables -D OUTPUT 5            //delete the 5th rule in the table
when DB server responds requests, a rule is not necessarily added to allow output connection from DB server, to validate this, on either server run:
$ netstat -an | grep 5432
